        </nav>
        
        <div class="content">
            <!-- OVERVIEW -->
            <section id="overview" class="section">
                <h2>Overview</h2>
                
                <div class="info-box">
                    <p><strong>General principle:</strong> Need for antimicrobial prophylaxis is based on duration and depth of neutropenia</p>
                </div>

                <div class="risk-box">
                    <h4>Risk-Based Approach</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Low Risk:</strong> Neutropenia <7 days → <strong>No prophylaxis needed</strong></li>
                        <li><strong>Intermediate/High Risk:</strong> Neutropenia >7 days → <strong>Prophylaxis indicated</strong></li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h3>Standard Antimicrobial Prophylaxis Categories</h3>

                <table>
                    <tr>
                        <th>Category</th>
                        <th>Standard Agent</th>
                        <th>Dose</th>
                        <th>When to Use</th>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td><strong>Antibacterial</strong></td>
                        <td>Levofloxacin</td>
                        <td>500 mg PO daily</td>
                        <td>During induction and when ANC <500</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td><strong>Antifungal</strong></td>
                        <td>Posaconazole<br>(or Fluconazole)</td>
                        <td>300 mg PO daily (after 300mg q12h × 2 doses loading)<br>400 mg PO daily</td>
                        <td>During induction and when ANC <500</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td><strong>Antiviral</strong></td>
                        <td>Acyclovir<br>(or Valacyclovir)</td>
                        <td>400 mg PO q12h<br>500 mg PO daily</td>
                        <td>During all chemotherapy</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td><strong>PJP (PCP)</strong></td>
                        <td>Bactrim DS<br>(or Atovaquone)</td>
                        <td>1 tab PO M/W/F or daily<br>1500 mg PO daily</td>
                        <td>When on steroids or lymphodepleting agents</td>
                    </tr>
                </table>

                <h3>Malignancy-Specific Considerations</h3>

                <div class="key-points">
                    <h4>🔑 Key Concept</h4>
                    <p><strong>Myeloid malignancies (AML, MDS):</strong> More likely to have side effects related to myeloid cells (neutrophils). Think fungal/bacterial infections that are normally killed by myeloid cells.</p>
                    <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Lymphoid malignancies (lymphoma, ALL, CLL):</strong> Treatments cause low lymphocytes. Think higher risk for viral infections and opportunistic infections (PJP, fungal).</p>
                </div>
            </section>

            <!-- BY DISEASE TABLE -->
            <section id="by-disease" class="section">
                <h2>Prophylaxis by Disease & Treatment</h2>

                <table>
                    <thead>
                        <tr>
                            <th style="width: 12%;">Diagnosis</th>
                            <th style="width: 22%;">Antibacterial</th>
                            <th style="width: 22%;">Antifungal</th>
                            <th style="width: 22%;">Anti-PCP</th>
                            <th style="width: 22%;">Antiviral</th>
                        </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>AML</strong></td>
                            <td>Levofloxacin during induction and when ANC <500</td>
                            <td>Posaconazole during induction and when ANC <500</td>
                            <td>Bactrim DS M/W/F if on purine analogs (ex: FLAG)</td>
                            <td>Acyclovir</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>MDS</strong></td>
                            <td>Levofloxacin during induction and when ANC <500</td>
                            <td>Posaconazole during induction and when ANC <500</td>
                            <td>None</td>
                            <td>Acyclovir</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>APML</strong></td>
                            <td>Levofloxacin during induction and when ANC <500</td>
                            <td>With prolonged neutropenia or anthracycline → Isovuconazole until resolution of neutropenia</td>
                            <td>Bactrim DS M/W/F if on steroids for >4 weeks (differentiation syndrome)</td>
                            <td>Acyclovir</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>ALL</strong></td>
                            <td>Levofloxacin during induction and when ANC <500</td>
                            <td><strong>Induction:</strong> Posaconazole<br><strong>Consolidation:</strong> Fluconazole when ANC <500<br><strong>If getting vincristine:</strong> Add micafungin</td>
                            <td>Bactrim DS M/W/F</td>
                            <td>Acyclovir</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Lymphoma</strong></td>
                            <td>Levofloxacin when ANC <500 for 7 days</td>
                            <td>Fluconazole when ANC <500 for 7 days</td>
                            <td>Bactrim DS M/W/F if on DA-EPOCH</td>
                            <td>Acyclovir</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Multiple Myeloma</strong></td>
                            <td>Levofloxacin when ANC <500 for 7 days</td>
                            <td>Fluconazole when ANC <500 for 7 days</td>
                            <td>None</td>
                            <td>Acyclovir</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>Solid Tumors</strong></td>
                            <td>Levofloxacin when ANC <500 for 7 days</td>
                            <td>Fluconazole when ANC <500 for 7 days</td>
                            <td>None</td>
                            <td>Acyclovir only if prior HSV episode</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>BiTE<br>(Immune-targeted)</strong></td>
                            <td>None</td>
                            <td>None</td>
                            <td>Bactrim DS M/W/F for ~6 months until CD4 recovery</td>
                            <td>Acyclovir</td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td><strong>CAR-T</strong></td>
                            <td>Only if prolonged neutropenia</td>
                            <td>Only if prolonged neutropenia</td>
                            <td>Bactrim DS M/W/F for ~6 months until CD4 recovery</td>
                            <td>Acyclovir</td>
                        </tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
            </section>

            <!-- MEDICATIONS DETAIL -->
            <section id="medications" class="section">
                <h2>Antimicrobial Medications - Details</h2>

                <h3>Antibacterial Prophylaxis</h3>

                <div class="info-box">
                    <h4>Levofloxacin 500 mg PO daily</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Coverage:</strong> Broad-spectrum fluoroquinolone (Gram-positive and Gram-negative)</li>
                        <li><strong>When to start:</strong> Beginning of chemotherapy or when ANC <500</li>
                        <li><strong>When to stop:</strong> ANC >500 × 2 consecutive days OR end of chemotherapy</li>
                        <li><strong>Considerations:</strong> Risk of C. difficile, resistance patterns, QTc prolongation</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h3>Antifungal Prophylaxis</h3>

                <div class="info-box">
                    <h4>Posaconazole (Noxafil) 300 mg PO daily</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Loading:</strong> 300 mg PO q12h × 2 doses (Day 1), then 300 mg daily</li>
                        <li><strong>Coverage:</strong> Broad mold coverage including Aspergillus, Mucor</li>
                        <li><strong>When to use:</strong> High-risk patients (AML, MDS, ALL induction)</li>
                        <li><strong>Must take with food</strong> for absorption</li>
                        <li><strong>Drug interaction:</strong> CYP3A4 inhibitor - reduces venetoclax dose to 100 mg</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="warning-box">
                    <h4>⚠️ Posaconazole/Voriconazole + Venetoclax Interaction</h4>
                    <p><strong>CRITICAL:</strong> If patient is on venetoclax:</p>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Posaconazole or voriconazole:</strong> Reduce venetoclax to <strong>100 mg daily</strong> (75% reduction)</li>
                        <li><strong>Fluconazole:</strong> Reduce venetoclax to <strong>200 mg daily</strong> (50% reduction)</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="info-box">
                    <h4>Isovuconazole (Cresemba)</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Loading:</strong> 372 mg q8h × 6 doses (48h), then 372 mg daily</li>
                        <li><strong>Coverage:</strong> Broad mold coverage, similar to posaconazole</li>
                        <li><strong>When to use:</strong> APL with prolonged neutropenia or anthracycline therapy</li>
                        <li><strong>Advantage:</strong> Can be given IV or PO, less drug interactions than posaconazole</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="info-box">
                    <h4>Fluconazole 400 mg PO daily</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Coverage:</strong> Candida species (NO mold coverage)</li>
                        <li><strong>When to use:</strong> Lower-risk patients, lymphoma, myeloma, consolidation ALL</li>
                        <li><strong>Advantage:</strong> Well-tolerated, fewer drug interactions than posaconazole</li>
                        <li><strong>Drug interaction:</strong> Moderate CYP3A4 inhibitor - reduces venetoclax to 200 mg</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="info-box">
                    <h4>Micafungin (Mycamine)</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Dose:</strong> 50 mg IV daily</li>
                        <li><strong>When to use:</strong> ALL patients receiving vincristine (risk of invasive candidiasis)</li>
                        <li><strong>Coverage:</strong> Candida species, some Aspergillus</li>
                        <li><strong>Advantage:</strong> No drug interactions, can use with azoles</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h3>Antiviral Prophylaxis</h3>

                <div class="info-box">
                    <h4>Acyclovir 400 mg PO q12h (or 400 mg PO TID)</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Coverage:</strong> HSV-1, HSV-2, VZV</li>
                        <li><strong>When to use:</strong> All patients receiving chemotherapy</li>
                        <li><strong>Duration:</strong> Throughout treatment and 6-12 months post-transplant/CAR-T</li>
                        <li><strong>Alternative:</strong> Valacyclovir 500 mg PO daily</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h3>PJP (Pneumocystis) Prophylaxis</h3>

                <div class="info-box">
                    <h4>Bactrim DS (TMP-SMX) M/W/F or Daily</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>Dose:</strong> 1 double-strength tablet (160/800 mg) PO</li>
                        <li><strong>Frequency:</strong> Monday/Wednesday/Friday OR daily</li>
                        <li><strong>When to use:</strong> Lymphodepleting therapy, steroids >20 mg prednisone × 1 month, ALL, BiTE, CAR-T</li>
                        <li><strong>Duration:</strong> Continue until CD4 count >200 for 3-6 months (BiTE/CAR-T)</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="warning-box">
                    <h4>⚠️ Bactrim Contraindications</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>G6PD deficiency:</strong> Risk of hemolysis - use atovaquone instead</li>
                        <li><strong>Methotrexate:</strong> Avoid Bactrim (interferes with MTX clearance) - use atovaquone</li>
                        <li><strong>Sulfa allergy:</strong> Use atovaquone or dapsone</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="info-box">
                    <h4>Atovaquone (Mepron) 1500 mg PO daily</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>When to use:</strong> Alternative to Bactrim (sulfa allergy, G6PD deficiency, on MTX)</li>
                        <li><strong>Must take with fatty food</strong> for absorption</li>
                        <li><strong>Expensive</strong> - insurance may require prior authorization</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="info-box">
                    <h4>Inhaled Pentamidine 300 mg monthly</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>When to use:</strong> Cannot tolerate oral medications</li>
                        <li><strong>Administration:</strong> Nebulized monthly in clinic</li>
                        <li><strong>Side effect:</strong> Bronchospasm (pre-treat with bronchodilator)</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </section>

            <!-- SPECIAL CONSIDERATIONS -->
            <section id="special" class="section">
                <h2>Special Considerations</h2>

                <h3>PJP Prophylaxis - Specific Indications</h3>

                <div class="key-points">
                    <h4>When to Give PJP Prophylaxis</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>ALL</strong> patients</li>
                        <li><strong>HCT</strong> (hematopoietic cell transplant) - continue until off immunosuppression</li>
                        <li><strong>Solid transplant</strong> while on immunosuppressive therapy</li>
                        <li><strong>CAR-T</strong> - for ~6 months until CD4 recovery</li>
                        <li><strong>Steroids ≥20 mg prednisone for ≥1 month</strong></li>
                        <li><strong>Specific medications:</strong> Alemtuzumab, polatuzumab, ibrutinib, BiTE therapies</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h3>Drug Interactions - Must Know</h3>

                <div class="warning-box">
                    <h4>⚠️ If on Methotrexate (High-Dose)</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>AVOID Bactrim</strong> - interferes with MTX clearance</li>
                        <li><strong>AVOID Dapsone</strong> - also interferes</li>
                        <li><strong>USE:</strong> Atovaquone or inhaled pentamidine for PJP prophylaxis</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <div class="warning-box">
                    <h4>⚠️ If G6PD Deficient</h4>
                    <ul>
                        <li><strong>AVOID Bactrim</strong> - risk of hemolysis</li>
                        <li><strong>AVOID Dapsone</strong> - risk of hemolysis</li>
                        <li><strong>USE:</strong> Atovaquone or inhaled pentamidine</li>
                    </ul>
                </div>

                <h3>When to Give IVIG</h3>

                <div class="info-box">
                    <h4>IVIG Replacement Indications</h4>
                    <p><strong>After CAR-T:</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>Check IgG levels monthly</li>
                        <li>If IgG <400 mg/dL with recurrent infections → start IVIG</li>
                        <li>If IgG <600 mg/dL (alternative threshold at some institutions)</li>
                    </ul>
                    
                    <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>After BiTE:</strong></p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>If IgG levels <400 mg/dL with recurrent infections</li>
                    </ul>

                    <p style="margin-top:10px;"><strong>Dose:</strong> 400-600 mg/kg IV every 3-4 weeks</p>
                </div>

                <h3>Duration of Prophylaxis</h3>

                <table>
                    <tr>
                        <th>Clinical Scenario</th>
                        <th>Stop Antibacterial</th>
                        <th>Stop Antifungal</th>
                        <th>Stop PJP Prophylaxis</th>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>Intensive chemotherapy (AML, ALL induction)</td>
                        <td>ANC >500 × 2 days</td>
                        <td>ANC >500 × 2 days</td>
                        <td>Continue through consolidation</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>Lymphoma chemotherapy</td>
                        <td>ANC >500 × 2 days OR after 7 days</td>
                        <td>ANC >500 × 2 days OR after 7 days</td>
                        <td>1 month after last chemo (if was on steroids)</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>CAR-T or BiTE</td>
                        <td>Only if prolonged neutropenia</td>
                        <td>Only if prolonged neutropenia</td>
                        <td>6 months OR until CD4 >200 × 3 months</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>High-dose steroids</td>
                        <td>N/A</td>
                        <td>N/A</td>
                        <td>Continue until off steroids + 4-6 weeks</td>
                    </tr>
                </table>
            </section>

            <!-- GLOSSARY -->
            <section id="glossary" class="glossary">
                <h3>📚 Abbreviations & Glossary</h3>
                
                <div class="abbrev">
                    <span class="abbrev-term">ANC</span>
                    <span>Absolute Neutrophil Count</span>
                    
                    <span class="abbrev-term">BiTE</span>
                    <span>Bispecific T-cell Engager</span>
                    
                    <span class="abbrev-term">CAR-T</span>
                    <span>Chimeric Antigen Receptor T-cell therapy</span>
                    
                    <span class="abbrev-term">G6PD</span>
                    <span>Glucose-6-Phosphate Dehydrogenase</span>
                    
                    <span class="abbrev-term">HCT</span>
                    <span>Hematopoietic Cell Transplant</span>
                    
                    <span class="abbrev-term">HSV</span>
                    <span>Herpes Simplex Virus</span>
                    
                    <span class="abbrev-term">IVIG</span>
                    <span>Intravenous Immunoglobulin</span>
                    
                    <span class="abbrev-term">MTX</span>
                    <span>Methotrexate</span>
                    
                    <span class="abbrev-term">PJP (PCP)</span>
                    <span>Pneumocystis jirovecii Pneumonia (formerly Pneumocystis carinii)</span>
                    
                    <span class="abbrev-term">PPX</span>
                    <span>Prophylaxis</span>
                    
                    <span class="abbrev-term">TMP-SMX</span>
                    <span>Trimethoprim-Sulfamethoxazole (Bactrim)</span>
                    
                    <span class="abbrev-term">VZV</span>
                    <span>Varicella Zoster Virus</span>
                </div>
            </section>
        </div>
    </div>
    
